Megatokyo can be found both on www.aniverse.com and www.megatokyo.com Maison Otaku can also be found on Aniverse. Life on Forbez is more like a sci-fi genre comedic strip and is located on www.forbez.com <br>
<br>
But I have a question. I think these artists do these strips as a hobby or a side project in their life so they pay for it out of their own pockets. But I think there's been an increasingly heightenign conflict of getting reimbursement for what used to be free stuff over the Internet. Like, it doesn't juts have to be online comics. But if a comic were good enough, would anyone buy the trade paperback of it? And do online comics have to be in the strip format for it to be accessible to the average internet viewer? I know of sites with more manga-like layouts looking more like a book instead of a strip but I don't think they have as big a fanbase as megatokyo. What do you guys think? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=arioch>Arioch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/10/02 5:43:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1413.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  reimbursement</span><hr size=1> There are a number of ways that webcomics creators are attempting to be remunerated for their work.<br>
<br>
First, there is online advertising. Currently, only the most heavily trafficked comics (such as PvP) earn much revenue from advertising. For most, it barely pays for hosting.<br>
<br>
Second, there is the sale of printed comics and other merchandise (mugs, t-shirts, etc.). It's my understanding that not many people want to buy a printed version of the webcomic they've already read, so most of the people I know who sell printed comics have to create new comics in addition to the webcomic, which is obviously a lot of work. Some people do sell printed anthologies of the webcomic, but I'd guess that sales from these barely cover the printing costs. Some webcomics are in a format that can easily be printed, and some are not. Some webcomics are created at a resolution high enough for printing, and some are not. In particular, color comics are very expensive to print.<br>
<br>
Third, the author can accept voluntary contributions via Paypal, Amazon, or some other service. I gather that some sites (such as Penny Arcade) survive primarily on this form of income.<br>
<br>
Fourth, a subscription cost can be charged for the webcomic. So far, I don't know of anyone who has succeeded with this. Moderntales.com is the latest group to try.<br>
<br>
Online comics are still a young medium. There are currently only a handful of creators who are able to make a living out of it. Only time will tell if there will be many more. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uokum.showPublicProfile?language=EN>okum</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/13/02 12:46:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1413.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  webcomics</span><hr size=1> My goal is to transcend the web and publish my work.  I am using the online comic as a sounding board for what works and what doesn't.  <br>
re. the coding and back buttons, etc.  Yeah, I get the idea you don't like the whold back button browser, but your response was well worth it.  (he he)... <br>
Honestly, I am working to get that sorted out.  I have done that on another site I did, and I should really do it for this one.  Thanks for the insight.<br>
re. making a living creating comics.  Mainstream comic artists can make a decent living creating one page of pencils for 75-100 dollars each. Multiply that by 22 and then a cover and any other work they can scrounge it's not too bad a gig.  It's getting to know the editors that's tough.  And, of course developing your skills to create the best pages you can. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utrekkieb47.showPublicProfile?language=EN>trekkieb47</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/15/02 12:05:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1413.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: webcomics</span><hr size=1> I'm really into www.frogchildren.com  ITS HILARIOUS!!!!!<br>
